Answer: \boxed{A}
Yes, cardenolides are inhibitors of Na+/K+ ATPase. Multiple sources confirm that cardiac glycosides—including digoxin, ouabain, and digitoxin—are well-documented inhibitors of the Na⁺/K⁺ ATPase pump. They bind specifically to the potassium-binding site, disrupting normal ion gradients, elevating intracellular sodium, and consequently increasing intracellular calcium via inhibition of the Na⁺/Ca²⁺ exchanger. This cascade leads to enhanced cardiac contractility, explaining their therapeutic use in heart failure and arrhythmias.
\boxed{A} Based on the retrieved evidence, we affirm that cardenolides do inhibit the Na⁺/K⁺ ATPase pump. All supporting references explicitly describe how cardiac glycosides such as digoxin and ouabain block the Na⁺/K⁺ ATPase by binding to its potassium site, leading to downstream physiological consequences involving calcium dysregulation and increased contractility. No contradictory findings were presented in any source. Therefore, the initial conclusion stands unchallenged.\boxed{A} We conclude definitively that cardenolides are indeed inhibitors of Na+/K+ ATPase.\boxed{A}
